@node "INSTALL" "SN LoginConfig v3.3 - Installation Procedures"
@toc "MAIN"
┌───────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  SN LoginConfig v3.3 - Installation Procedures
└───────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  (The installation script handles updates from previous versions
   without harming your existing setup.  Don't be shy!)

 1  Run the included installation script either of the following
    two ways:

    a.  Type "Installer Install_LogFig" from the Shell.

    b.  Click on the "Install_LogFig" icon from Workbench.

 2  The installation script moves the required files to your specified
    location, including adding a CNet help file called "LOGIN."

 3  The installation script also copies your current sys.welcome to
    sys.welcome.bak AND to LogFig/_All-YOURS, renames the included
    _All to _All-MINE (this is mine I've included for an example) and
    finally replaces your sys.welcome with NEW.sys.welcome.  This new
    sys.welcome runs the program, SN_LoginConfig.

 4  Edit the _#? files to the way you want your users to be able to
    configure their logins.

    a.  The FIRST MANDATORY files executed should be placed in _Begin.

    b.  The MIDDLE OPTIONAL files executed should be placed in _Added.
        Note the format of the example file!  First line is the actual
        execution command and the second is the description of it the users
        will see.

    c.  The LAST MANDATORY files executed should be placed in _End.

    d.  The special login sequences, _HiSpeed, _LDSpeed and _NewUser,
        should be modified to suit, also.  They are what the respective
        users see if opted for (in the case of the first two.)  New users
        always use the _NewUser sequence.

    (Included are my files for you to follow.  They're just like your
    normal sys.welcome files, so it's no biggie.)

 5  _All-YOURS should now be your old sys.welcome file.  It's safe to
    just rename _All-YOURS to _All, but I've left that up to you,
    because you're probably going to be making alot of changes.  (Moving
    this line to this file, etc.)  A good way to reconstruct your _All
    is to, first, edit _Begin, Added and End.  Once done, your _All
    should be your _Begin on top, your _Added (without descriptions, of
    course) in the middle and your _End on the bottom.  AND!!!  You need
    to add one more line to your _All once it's ready.  That line is
    included in the file _Add2EndOf_All.

 6  Modify SysOp configurable variables in LogFig/SN_LoginConfig:

    a.  localc="910 919"   /* (*=ALL) Local Area Codes */
        hiaccs="10 30 31"  /* (*=ALL) Levels Allowed to Use HiSpeed */
        mraccs="*"         /* (*=ALL) Levels Allowed to Use OMR-Grabber/Upload */
        mcaccs="*"         /* (*=ALL) Levels Allowed to Use MailCheck */
        skiprs="1 72"      /* (*=ALL) UserIDs Allowed to Skip Login */
        showfirst=0        /* Show _All before users configure? (0=NO) */
        logging=2          /* 0=None, 1=CNet, 2=SN Userlogs, 3=Both */
        askem=0            /* Ask/Force customize 0=FORCE 1=ASK */

    b.  The local area codes line is used to determine who should be
        allowed to use the LDSpeed login.  Use as many as needed in your
        area, seperated by a space.  (Follow the example.)  The next three
        govern what levels get to see the special pre-logins.  The skip
        login uses ID#'s instead of levels, allowing only one or a certain
        few to skip the entire login sequence.  Note that using "*" will
        allow ALL access levels to use it.

    c.  ShowFirst determines whether you want users who have NOT selected
        a config yet to see everything in the _All BEFORE they get to
        choose.  If yes, they'll go through everything, then be asked
        to customize.  Otherwise, they'll be asked to customize first and
        go from there.

    d.  Logging:  4 options here.  First is no logging.  You'll never know
        what choice users made unless you're watching.  Second adds a
        line telling you what they did in CNet's calls log.  Third adds
        the line to SN's UserLogs.  The last option does both.

    e.  When LoginConfig is executed, either automatically from the
        end of your default _All or manually by the LOGIN command,
        this determines whether the user is asked or forced to customize
        their login sequence.  If it's not forced and they say no, they
        will continue using the default login sequence (_All) until they
        opt to do so.

 7  Make the required BBSTEXT/BBSMENU modifications:

    ** See the now seperate file, LF33_Cut-n-Paste, for details on all
       BBSTEXT/BBSMENU modifications.

 8  Verify that your new sys.welcome says:
       {#0SN:LogFig/SN_LoginConfig}

    If it doesn't for some reason, make it so.

 9  Add "LOGIN |{#0SN:LogFig/SN_LoginConfig CONFIG}" to your bbsmenu (and add
    the option to your main menu) so users can modify their configurations
    at will after their first login with the default sequence.  Note that
    the above { is actually a control-Q command.

10  Add "LCRESET |{#1SN:LogFig/SN_LoginConfig RESET}" to your bbsmenu under
    "1; Maintenance menu."  When ran, it will reset all your users configs,
    in case you change your _Added config file and want them to use the
    new one (duh).

    ** Note for 8-10 above:  Modify the path to reflect your setup!

11  Reload your bbstext/bbsmenu via CNet's Control Panel menu (option
    #3, "Text/menu reload  RAmiga-T" and you're all set!

